SubRuleContent: Source files are encoded in UTF-8.
Project: <property name="charset" value="UTF-8"/>
Violation: Source files must be encoded in UTF-8.
Explanation: This property sets the expected charset for reading source files, and can prevent issues when the encoding mismatches. However, it does not enforce or report violations if the file is not UTF-8 encoded.

SubRuleContent:
Aside from the line terminator sequence, the ASCII horizontal space character (0x20) is the only whitespace character that appears anywhere in a source file. This implies that:

All other whitespace characters in string and character literals are escaped.
Tab characters are not used for indentation.
Project:
<module name="FileTabCharacter">
        <property name="eachLine" value="true"/>
    </module>
    <module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="RegexpSinglelineJava">
            <property name="format" value="[\u0008\f\v\u00A0\u2002-\u200D\u202F\u3000\r]"/>
            <property name="message" value="Disallowed whitespace character detected."/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Disallowed whitespace character detected.
Explanation: Checkstyle provides FileTabCharacter to detect tab characters specifically. Although it does not natively support checking for other disallowed whitespace characters, this rule is fully supported when combined with RegexpSinglelineJava to match additional characters such as form feed (\f), vertical tab (\v), and non-breaking space (U+00A0).

SubRuleContent: For any character that has a special escape sequence (\b, \t, \n, \f, \r, \", \' and \\), that sequence is used rather than the corresponding octal (e.g. \012) or Unicode (e.g. \u000a) escape.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="IllegalTokenText">
            <property name="tokens" value="STRING_LITERAL, CHAR_LITERAL"/>
            <property name="format"
                value="\\u00(08|09|0(a|A)|0(c|C)|0(d|D)|22|27|5(C|c)|a0)|\\(0(10|11|12|14|15|42|47)|134|u200[2-9a-dA-D]|u202F|u3000)"/>
            <property name="message"
                   value="Consider using special escape sequence instead of octal value or Unicode escaped value."/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Consider using special escape sequence instead of octal value or Unicode escaped value.

SubRuleContent:
A source file consists of, in order:
1.License or copyright information, if present
2.Package statement
3.Import statements
4.Exactly one top-level class
Violation: Line does not match expected header line of '/*'.
Explanation: Checkstyle can only verify that license headers appear at the very top of a file. It does not support enforcing the specific order of other top-level components such as package, import, or class declarations. As a result, enforcing strict file component ordering is not reliably supported.

SubRuleContent:
A source file consists of, in order:
1.License or copyright information, if present
2.Package statement
3.Import statements
4.Exactly one top-level class
Violation: Each source file consists of, in order: a license/copyright header (if present), package declaration, import statements, and a top-level class.
Explanation: Checkstyle can only verify that license headers appear at the very top of a file. It does not support enforcing the specific order of other top-level components such as package, import, or class declarations. As a result, enforcing strict file component ordering is not reliably supported.

SubRuleContent:
Imports are ordered as follows:

All static imports in a single block.
All non-static imports in a single block. Within each block the imported names appear in ASCII sort order. (Note: this is not the same as the import statements being in ASCII sort order, since '.' sorts before ';'.)
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="CustomImportOrder">
            <property name="sortImportsInGroupAlphabetically" value="true"/>
            <property name="customImportOrderRules" value="STATIC, THIRD_PARTY_PACKAGE"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Wrong lexicographical order for 'java.util.ArrayList' import. Should be before 'java.util.Map'.
Explanation: Checkstyle reports violations in import group placement first. If an import is placed in the wrong group, it will skip checking the alphabetical order within that group. As a result, incorrect intra-group ordering may go unreported when inter-group misplacement exists.

            <property name="sortImportsInGroupAlphabetically" value="true"/>
            <property name="customImportOrderRules" value="STATIC, THIRD_PARTY_PACKAGE"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Wrong lexicographical order for 'java.lang.Math.PI' import. Should be before 'java.lang.Math.abs'.
Explanation: Checkstyle reports violations in import group placement first. If an import is placed in the wrong group, it will skip checking the alphabetical order within that group. As a result, incorrect intra-group ordering may go unreported when inter-group misplacement exists.

SubRuleContent: Static import is not used for static nested classes. They are imported with normal imports.
Violation: Static import of nested classes is not allowed.
Explanation: The AvoidStaticImport check can only ban all static imports, but it cannot selectively detect static imports of nested classes. As a result, it cannot enforce the rule that specifically prohibits static imports of static nested classes.

RuleContent: 3.5.1 Ordering and spacing of module directives

Module directives are ordered as follows:

All requires directives in a single block.
All exports directives in a single block.
All opens directives in a single block.
All uses directives in a single block.
All provides directives in a single block.

SubRuleContent: Braces are used with if, else, for, do and while statements, even when the body is empty or contains only a single statement.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="NeedBraces">
            <property name="tokens" value="LITERAL_DO, LITERAL_ELSE, LITERAL_FOR, LITERAL_IF, LITERAL_WHILE"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: 'if' construct must use '{}'s.
Explanation: Checkstyle does not build an AST for module-info.java files, so it cannot check blank lines between module directive blocks.

Violation: "The concise form {} is not allowed in multi-block statements such as if/else or try/catch/finally."
Explanation: The RightCurly check can enforce 'alone' style braces for certain tokens like 'finally', preventing illegal concise forms within multi-block constructs. However, Checkstyle does not provide a token or mechanism to enforce brace placement specifically for multi-block structures as a whole, so violations like empty blocks in try-catch-finally cannot be fully checked. As a result, support is limited.

SubRuleContent:
Java code has a column limit of 100 characters. A "character" means any Unicode code point. Except as noted below, any line that would exceed this limit must be line-wrapped, as explained in Section 4.5, Line-wrapping.

Each Unicode code point counts as one character, even if its display width is greater or less. For example, if using fullwidth characters, you may choose to wrap the line earlier than where this rule strictly requires.
Project:
<module name="LineLength">
        <property name="fileExtensions" value="java"/>
        <property name="max" value="100"/>
    </module>
Violation: Line is longer than 100 characters (found 110).

SubRuleContent:
1. When a line is broken at a non-assignment operator the break comes before the symbol. (Note that this is not the same practice used in Google style for other languages, such as C++ and JavaScript.)
·This also applies to the following "operator-like" symbols:
-the dot separator (.)
-the two colons of a method reference (::)
-an ampersand in a type bound (<T extends Foo & Bar>)
-a pipe in a catch block (catch (FooException | BarException e)).
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="OperatorWrap">
            <property name="option" value="NL"/>
            <property name="tokens"
                   value="BAND, BOR, BSR, BXOR, DIV, EQUAL, GE, GT, LAND, LE, LITERAL_INSTANCEOF, LOR,
                        LT, MINUS, MOD, NOT_EQUAL, PLUS, QUESTION, SL, SR, STAR, METHOD_REF,
                        TYPE_EXTENSION_AND"/>
        </module>
        <module name="SeparatorWrap">
            <property name="id" value="SeparatorWrapDot"/>
            <property name="tokens" value="DOT"/>
            <property name="option" value="nl"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: '.' should be on a new line.

SubRuleContent:
A single blank line always appears:

1. Between consecutive members or initializers of a class: fields, constructors, methods, nested classes, static initializers, and instance initializers.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="EmptyLineSeparator">
            <property name="tokens"
                   value="CLASS_DEF, INTERFACE_DEF, ENUM_DEF,
                        STATIC_INIT, INSTANCE_INIT, METHOD_DEF, CTOR_DEF, VARIABLE_DEF, RECORD_DEF,
                        COMPACT_CTOR_DEF"/>
            <property name="allowNoEmptyLineBetweenFields" value="true"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: 'STATIC_INIT' should be separated from previous line.
Explanation: The EmptyLineSeparator check treats all CLASS_DEF equally and does not distinguish between nested and top-level classes. This may lead to false positives when multiple top-level classes are declared in the same file, as it can incorrectly require empty lines between them.

SubRuleContent: 1. Separating any reserved word, such as if, for or catch, from an open parenthesis (() that follows it on that line
Project:
<module name="WhitespaceAfter">
            <property name="tokens"
                   value="LITERAL_IF, LITERAL_ELSE, LITERAL_RETURN,
                        LITERAL_WHILE, LITERAL_DO, LITERAL_FOR, LITERAL_FINALLY, DO_WHILE,
                        LITERAL_SWITCH, LITERAL_SYNCHRONIZED, LITERAL_TRY, LITERAL_CATCH,
                        LITERAL_YIELD, LITERAL_CASE, LITERAL_WHEN"/>
        </module>
Violation: 'if' is not followed by whitespace.
Explanation: The WhitespaceAfter check only verifies the presence of at least one space after reserved keywords like 'if', 'for', or 'while'. It does not validate the exact number of spaces, so multiple spaces are not flagged, making this rule only partially supported.

This leads to under-support due to lack of precision and over-support because it may incorrectly check for spacing after the brace, which is outside the rule's intent.

SubRuleContent:
3. Before any open curly brace ({), with two exceptions:
·@SomeAnnotation({a, b}) (no space is used)
·String[][] x = {{"foo"}}; (no space is required between {{, by item 9 below)

SubRuleContent:
4. On both sides of any binary or ternary operator. This also applies to the following "operator-like" symbols:
·the ampersand in a conjunctive type bound: <T extends Foo & Bar>
·the pipe for a catch block that handles multiple exceptions: catch (FooException | BarException e)
·the colon (:) in an enhanced for ("foreach") statement
·the arrow in a lambda expression: (String str) -> str.length()
but not
·the two colons (::) of a method reference, which is written like Object::toString
·the dot separator (.), which is written like object.toString()

SubRuleContent:
4. On both sides of any binary or ternary operator. This also applies to the following "operator-like" symbols:
·the ampersand in a conjunctive type bound: <T extends Foo & Bar>
·the pipe for a catch block that handles multiple exceptions: catch (FooException | BarException e)
·the colon (:) in an enhanced for ("foreach") statement
·the arrow in a lambda expression: (String str) -> str.length()
but not
·the two colons (::) of a method reference, which is written like Object::toString
·the dot separator (.), which is written like object.toString()

            <property name="allowEmptyMethods" value="true"/>
            <property name="allowEmptyTypes" value="true"/>
            <property name="allowEmptyLoops" value="true"/>
            <property name="allowEmptySwitchBlockStatements" value="true"/>
            <property name="ignoreEnhancedForColon" value="false"/>

                    BXOR_ASSIGN, COLON, DIV, DIV_ASSIGN, DO_WHILE, EQUAL, GE, GT, LAMBDA, LAND,
                    LE, LOR, LT, MINUS, MINUS_ASSIGN, MOD, MOD_ASSIGN,
                    NOT_EQUAL, PLUS, PLUS_ASSIGN, QUESTION, SL, SL_ASSIGN, SR,
                    SR_ASSIGN, STAR, STAR_ASSIGN,
                    TYPE_EXTENSION_AND"/>
        </module>

        </module>

SubRuleContent:
Every variable declaration (field or local) declares only one variable: declarations such as int a, b; are not used.

Exception: Multiple variable declarations are acceptable in the header of a for loop.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="MultipleVariableDeclarations"/>
    </module>
Violation: Each variable declaration must be in its own statement.
Explanation: The MultipleVariableDeclarations check enforces that each variable must be declared in its own statement. Although it does not expose configuration options to control exceptions, it automatically ignores multiple variable declarations in the header of a for loop, which aligns with the rule’s exception.

SubRuleContent: The Java language requires switch expressions and many kinds of switch statements to be exhaustive. That effectively means that every possible value that could be switched on will be matched by one of the switch labels. A switch is exhaustive if it has a default label, but also for example if the value being switched on is an enum and every value of the enum is matched by a switch label. Google Style requires every switch to be exhaustive, even those where the language itself does not require it. This may require adding a default label, even if it contains no code.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="MissingSwitchDefault"/>
    </module>
Violation: switch without "default" clause.

SubRuleContent: A method is marked with the @Override annotation whenever it is legal. This includes a class method overriding a superclass method, a class method implementing an interface method, and an interface method respecifying a superinterface method.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name='MissingOverride'/>
    </module>
Violation: Missing @Override annotation on method that overrides a superclass or interface method.
Explanation: Violations of this guideline cannot be detected by Checkstyle due to its limitation, multiple file checking is not supported. The MissingOverride check may fail to report violations when the there is no inheritDoc.

SubRuleContent:
It is very rarely correct to do nothing in response to a caught exception. (Typical responses are to log it, or if it is considered "impossible", rethrow it as an AssertionError.)

When it truly is appropriate to take no action whatsoever in a catch block, the reason this is justified is explained in a comment.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="EmptyCatchBlock">
            <property name="exceptionVariableName" value="expected"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Empty catch block.

SubRuleContent:
When a reference to a static class member must be qualified, it is qualified with that class's name, not with a reference or expression of that class's type.

Foo aFoo = ...;
Foo.aStaticMethod(); // good
aFoo.aStaticMethod(); // bad
somethingThatYieldsAFoo().aStaticMethod(); // very bad
Violation: Do not invoke static methods through instance references.
Explanation: Violations of this guideline cannot be detected by Checkstyle due to its limitation, multiple file checking is not supported.

SubRuleContent:
When a reference to a static class member must be qualified, it is qualified with that class's name, not with a reference or expression of that class's type.

Foo aFoo = ...;
Foo.aStaticMethod(); // good
aFoo.aStaticMethod(); // bad
somethingThatYieldsAFoo().aStaticMethod(); // very bad
Violation: Do not invoke static methods via expressions. Use the class name instead.
Explanation: Violations of this guideline cannot be detected by Checkstyle due to its limitation, multiple file checking is not supported.

SubRuleContent:
At the minimum, Javadoc is present for every visible class, member, or record component, with a few exceptions noted below. A top-level class is visible if it is public; a member is visible if it is public or protected and its containing class is visible; and a record component is visible if its containing record is visible.

Additional Javadoc content may also be present, as explained in Section 7.3.4, Non-required Javadoc.
Project:
<module name="TreeWalker">
        <module name="JavadocVariable">
            <property name="accessModifiers" value="public, protected"/>
        </module>
        <module name="MissingJavadocMethod">
            <property name="scope" value="protected"/>
            <property name="allowMissingPropertyJavadoc" value="true"/>
            <property name="allowedAnnotations" value="Override, Test"/>
            <property name="tokens" value="METHOD_DEF, CTOR_DEF, ANNOTATION_FIELD_DEF,
                                       COMPACT_CTOR_DEF"/>
        </module>
        <module name="MissingJavadocType">
            <property name="scope" value="protected"/>
            <property name="tokens"
                    value="CLASS_DEF, INTERFACE_DEF, ENUM_DEF,
                          RECORD_DEF, ANNOTATION_DEF"/>
            <property name="excludeScope" value="nothing"/>
        </module>
        <module name="InvalidJavadocPosition"/>
        <module name="SuppressionXpathSingleFilter">
            <property name="checks" value="JavadocVariable, MissingJavadocMethod, MissingJavadocType"/>
            <property name="query" value="//*[self::VARIABLE_DEF or self::METHOD_DEF or self::CTOR_DEF or self::CLASS_DEF or self::INTERFACE_DEF or self::ENUM_DEF or self::RECORD_DEF or self::ANNOTATION_DEF]
            [ancestor::*[self::METHOD_DEF or self::CLASS_DEF or self::INTERFACE_DEF or self::ENUM_DEF or self::RECORD_DEF or self::ANNOTATION_DEF]
             [not(./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PUBLIC or ./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PROTECTED)]
            or not(ancestor::*[not(ancestor::*)][./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PUBLIC])]"/>
        </module>
    </module>

            <property name="accessModifiers" value="public, protected"/>
        </module>
        <module name="MissingJavadocMethod">
            <property name="scope" value="protected"/>
            <property name="allowMissingPropertyJavadoc" value="true"/>
            <property name="allowedAnnotations" value="Override, Test"/>
            <property name="tokens" value="METHOD_DEF, CTOR_DEF, ANNOTATION_FIELD_DEF,
                                       COMPACT_CTOR_DEF"/>
        </module>
        <module name="MissingJavadocType">
            <property name="scope" value="protected"/>
            <property name="tokens"
                    value="CLASS_DEF, INTERFACE_DEF, ENUM_DEF,
                          RECORD_DEF, ANNOTATION_DEF"/>
            <property name="excludeScope" value="nothing"/>
        </module>
        <module name="InvalidJavadocPosition"/>
        <module name="SuppressionXpathSingleFilter">
            <property name="checks" value="JavadocVariable, MissingJavadocMethod, MissingJavadocType"/>
            <property name="query" value="//*[self::VARIABLE_DEF or self::METHOD_DEF or self::CTOR_DEF or self::CLASS_DEF or self::INTERFACE_DEF or self::ENUM_DEF or self::RECORD_DEF or self::ANNOTATION_DEF]
            [ancestor::*[self::METHOD_DEF or self::CLASS_DEF or self::INTERFACE_DEF or self::ENUM_DEF or self::RECORD_DEF or self::ANNOTATION_DEF]
             [not(./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PUBLIC or ./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PROTECTED)]
            or not(ancestor::*[not(ancestor::*)][./MODIFIERS/LITERAL_PUBLIC])]"/>
        </module>
    </module>
Violation: Missing a Javadoc comment.
Explanation: Supported, but the configuration of xpath is complex.

SubRuleContent:
At the minimum, Javadoc is present for every visible class, member, or record component, with a few exceptions noted below. A top-level class is visible if it is public; a member is visible if it is public or protected and its containing class is visible; and a record component is visible if its containing record is visible.

Additional Javadoc content may also be present, as explained in Section 7.3.4, Non-required Javadoc.
